@NODE INFO "Introduction"

 Despite it's great funtionality, Final  Writer  97  still  lacks  support  for
 footnotes.  This  makes it almost impossible to create scientific articles and
 other things that require footnotes. FinalFootnotes tries to provide you  with
 a replacement for this. It allows you to use footnotes within Final Writer 97,
 still with some effort but much less than doing everything by hand.

 The idea is simple: You keep typing in the numbers of the footnotes  yourself,
 but  you  don't  have  to  worry  about  whether  the  numbers you used are in
 increasing order or not (which is a real pain if you want to add one  later!).
 When you've finished your document (or when you want to print it), simply call
 FinalFootnotes to replace these arbitrary  numbers  with  increasing  footnote
 numbers. The footnotes themselves can be typed in a textframe at the bottom of
 the page.
@ENDNODE
@NODE INSTALL "Installation"

 Simply copy the macros to your FWMacros directory. You can use  the  Installer
 script for this:

    @{"Start installation" SYSTEM "Installer FinalFootnotes.install APPNAME FinalFootnotes MINUSER EXPERT NOPRETEND NOLOG NOPRINTER"}
@ENDNODE
@NODE USAGE "Usage"

 @{B}FinalFootnotes@{UB}

 To distinguish your footnotes from other text, two methods are used:  You  can
 precede  every  footnote  and reference to a footnote with a special character
 (like #,@,§ etc.) which doesn't appear anywhere in your document. You can also
 embrace the references with two characters (like [ and ]). Instead of that (or
 in addition to it) you can tell FinalFootnotes to look for footnotes  only  in
 text written in superscript or subscript. Besides that you can chose arbitrary
 names for your footnotes and references (not only numbers).

 FinalFootnotes will first ask you to save your document (as  it  will  perform
 possibly  irreversible  modifications).  Then you may choose in which position
 your references appear (superscript, subscript, normal).  FinalFootnotes  will
 only  look  for  references in that position. You will then be asked to give a
 prefix and postfix character (if you enter just one, that will  be  considered
 the  prefix,  if you enter two the first will be the prefix and the second the
 postfix). If you enter nothing, no prefix will be used. Note that you have  to
 specify  either  a  prefix  and  postix or a position where the references may
 appear (after all there must be some  way  to  distinguish  them  from  normal
 text!). FinalFootnotes expects all references to start with the prefix and end
 with the postfix (or a space if no postfix is given). Only such references are
 processed.

 Then you will be prompted for the number of the first footnote. FinalFootnotes
 allows for the following numbering systems:

 - Decimal: 1, 2, 3, ...
 - Lowercase letters: a, b, c, ..., z, aa, ab, ...
 - Uppercase letters: A, B, C, ..., Z, AA, AB, ...
 - Asterisks: *, **, ***, ...

 Usually you would enter one of 1, a, A, or *. You may also start  with  higher
 numbers  (e.g.  if you want continuous numbering through different sections or
 documents). You also may specify arbitrary  characters  before  or  after  the
 number.  These  will  be added to each footnote. (FinalFootnotes will look for
 the first letter, number or asterisk starting from the end of what you entered
 to determine what system is to be used.)

 E.g. You could type (5).  In  this  case  FinalFootnotes  would  generate  the
 footnotes (5), (6), (7) etc.

 Finally you can choose in which  position  the  footnotes  should  be  printed
 (superscript,  subscript or normal). This allows you to use the prefix/postfix
 mechanism to identify references and still generate superscript footnotes.

 FinalFootnotes then searches the main text section as well as all text  frames
 for  the  pattern  and replaces the matching passages with increasing numbers,
 where equal passages are replaced by the same numbers.

 E.g. Your initial document:

  This is a simple[a] text which does not make much sense[c], but merely serves
  an exemplary purpose[b].

  ---
  [a] In terms of complexity.
  [c] This of course depends on your point of view!
  [b] As to demonstrate facts.

 You would specify the position as "Normal", and the  prefix/postfix  as  "[]".
 The output should be numbers in super script. FinalFootnotes will generate the
 following:

  This is a simpleą text which does not make much sense˛, but merely  serves an
  exemplary purposeł.

  ---
  ą In terms of complexity.
  ˛ This of course depends on your point of view!
  ł As to demonstrate facts.

 When the job is done, FinalFootnotes will report on how many  references  were
 found  and  whether  there  were any problems. If anything went wrong, you can
 request a more detailed report on the errors. Two things can happen:

 - There can be references that are unmatched, i.e. where the  same  name  does
 not  occur  exactly  twice. This should normally be the case for footnotes. If
 you accidentally got this wrong, you  should  reload  the  original  document,
 modify  the  reference  names,  save the document again and run FinalFootnotes
 again.

 - There can be references with the same name that are not on  the  same  page.
 You would normally want footnotes to appear on the same page on which they are
 referenced. This can be a little tricky  to  get  right  as  the  document  is
 modified  by  FinalFootnotes and therefore a reference could appear on another
 page as in the original document. You should  generally  use  short  reference
 names  to  avoid  this.  You  might  need  to try a couple of times to get the
 footnote on the right page (or move the footnote to the  correct  place  after
 running FinalFootnotes).

 @{B}FinalFrameToFootnote@{UB}

 Before running this macro, select a text frame. The macro will simply increase
 the page's footer area to include the selected frame and draw a small vertical
 line above the frame as it is usually done to separate footnote sections.
@ENDNODE
